Converts pre-formatted `@literal` block templates (multi-line data structures like nested braces) into a keystroke `Event` IR that drives a *smart auto-indenting editor* rather than typing raw text — the core trick of the whole crate's v2 emitter for this chunk kind. Because such editors auto-close every `{`, auto-indent lines, and block-expand on `{`+Enter, this module never emits literal tabs or closing-brace-only lines; it instead emits `Enter`/`Down`/`End` navigation to land the cursor where auto-supplied structure already put it, then types only the remaining text.

`struct_text(template: &[Chunk]) -> String` renders a template to raw text (tabs/newlines/braces) — used only internally by `struct_lines`, and as a building block, ignores `Chunk::Landing`/`Chunk::TypeSlot`-like variants since `@literal` blocks never contain them (silently no-ops on any chunk it doesn't recognize, so adding a new `Chunk` variant that can legally appear in `@literal` blocks requires updating this match or text silently drops).

`emit_struct(template: &[Chunk]) -> Vec<Event>` is the public entry point. It first strips blank lines and `}`-only lines via `struct_lines` (closers are never typed — the editor auto-supplies them), then walks remaining lines emitting `Event::Text` plus navigation from `nav()`. Key non-obvious behaviors: a line whose content starts with `}` (e.g. `} else {`) is treated as a "closer" line — it appends onto the editor's existing auto-`}` rather than opening a new one, so only `content[1..]` is typed for it. Navigating from a deeper previous line back to a shallower sibling (`!prev_opens && line.depth < prev_depth`) requires walking `Down` past the auto-closed braces, hitting `End`, then `Enter` — this is the "drop K levels" case from the module doc. All other transitions (line after an opener, sibling at same depth) collapse to a single `Enter`, per the doc comment noting three cases from the original TS implementation reduce to one branch here.

Depends on `crate::editor::{Event, KeyName}` (the keystroke IR consumed downstream by whatever drives the actual editor) and `crate::parse::Chunk` (the parsed template representation). Indentation in the emitted text is never the template's tab characters — the editor's own indent unit (4 spaces, per module doc) governs the final visual result, so `SLine.depth`/tabs here are only used for computing navigation deltas, not for producing indentation text.